Currently when I want to create a reusable button component for default styling, there is no elegant way to allow all default html button attributes for the button. In React it can be done like this

```ts
import React from 'react';

type ButtonProps = {
	variant?: 'solid' | 'outline';
} & React.ButtonHTMLAttributes<HTMLButtonElement>;

const Button = ({
	variant = 'solid',
	...props
}: ButtonProps) => {
	return (
		<button
			{...props}
			className={variant}
		/>
	);
};

export default Button;
```
And then I can easily use any attribute I want, and it even gives me intellisense
```jsx
<Button variant="outline" onClick={someFunc} type="submit" />
```

However in Svelte, as far as I can see, there are two ways to do this neither of which are very good. The first is to use `$$props`:
```svelte
<script lang="ts">
      export let variant: "solid" | "outline" = "solid"
</script>

<button {...$$props} class={variant} >
      <slot />
</button>
```
However this does not give me intellisense when using it somewhere else, and events are not forwarded among other things
```svelte
<Button variant="outline" on:click={isNotForwarded} type="submit"  />
```

The other way is to explicitly specify every single attribute possible for an html button, and forward the events manually
```svelte
<script lang="ts">
      export let variant: "solid" | "outline" = "solid";
      export let type: string = "button";
      // All other attributes
</script>

<button {...$$props} {type} on:click class={variant} /* Handle other forwarding and stuff */ >
      <slot />
</button>
```
However that quickly becomes a very large file, boilerplate-y, and boring to write

Now I propose something more similar to React
```svelte
<script lang="ts">
	type ButtonProps = {
		variant?: 'solid' | 'outline';
	} & svelte.JSX.DOMAttributes<HTMLButtonElement> &
		svelte.JSX.HTMLAttributes<HTMLButtonElement>;
        // or maybe something more succinct if it exists

	export let {variant = "solid", ...props}: ButtonProps;
</script>

<button {...props} class={variant}>
	<slot />
</button>
```
And then you could use it like this and get intellisense, automatic event forwarding
```svelte
<Button variant="outline" on:click={someFunc} type="submit" />
```

An alternative could also be to strongly type the $$props to get intellisense, and automatically forward events.

