Attempting to "fix" this by myself, I'm currently trying to wrap this line:
https://github.com/sveltejs/svelte/blob/c4479d976b2fbb00ffd08980de58f12ac20b7f2f/src/compiler/compile/render_dom/invalidate.ts#L69
in a conditional statement which would prevent this line:

`childRefs[child].propNum = 1`

to be compiled as:

`$$invalidate(0, childRefs[child].propNum = 1, childRefs)`

if a component has the corresponding acccessor / was compiled with the `accessors = {true}` option.

So far I've came up with this:

```javascript
let leftObj
let leftPropName

if(node.left?.property?.name) leftPropName = node.left.property.name
if((node.left?.object?.type === 'Identifier')) leftObj = node.left.object.name
if((node.left?.object?.type === 'MemberExpression')) leftObj = node.left.object
					
// if 'node.left' is Identifier.Identifier or MemberExpression.Identifier
if(leftObj && leftPropName) {

  // will render as conditional statement
  // if 'node.left.object' references a component and this component has a setter with the 'name' of 'node.left.property'
  invalidate = b `if (${leftObj}.$$ && Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor(Object.getPrototypeOf(${leftObj}), "${leftPropName}").set) {
    ${extra_args.length ? [node, ...extra_args] : node}
  } else {
    $$invalidate(${renderer.context_lookup.get(head.name).index}, ${node}, ${extra_args})
  }`[0]

} else {
  invalidate = x `$$invalidate(${renderer.context_lookup.get(head.name).index}, ${node}, ${extra_args})`;
}
```

this will compile `childRefs[child].propNum = 1` as:
```javascript
if (childRefs["child"].$$ && Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor(Object.getPrototypeOf(childRefs["child"]), "propNum").set) {
    childRefs["child"].propNum = 1;
} else {
    $$invalidate(1, childRefs["child"].propNum = 2, childRefs);
}
```
which will leave `childRefs["child"].propNum = 1` as it is and will update only the corresponding `child`, nothing else.

I've already tested it in a pretty complicated / extreme performance demanding project and while it's not breaking anything and I believe to see better performance than before (have no exact numbers yet), it seems the `getOwnPropertyDescriptor`-check is expensive. Unfortunately I don't see any component-property that would indicate it was compiled with the `accessors = {true}` option and I wasn't able to find some `svelte/internal` function (yet) that would perform that check.

If something like `$$.acc` (boolean) would be available it'd probably make the check much faster:
```javascript
// will render as conditional statement
// if 'node.left.object' references a component and this component was compiled with `accessors = {true}`
invalidate = b `if (${leftObj}.$$?.acc) { ...
``` 
Next I'll try to inject the `acc` indicator (somewhere) + test the accessors-check speed with that.

> Next I'll try to inject the acc indicator (somewhere) + test the accessors-check speed with that.

ok, this:

```javascript
if(component.component_options.accessors) {
  accessors.push({
    type: 'MethodDefinition',
    kind: 'get',
    key: { type: 'Identifier', name: '$component_compiled_with_accessors' },
    value: x `function() {
    return true
  }`
 });
}
```

inserted here: https://github.com/sveltejs/svelte/blob/c4479d976b2fbb00ffd08980de58f12ac20b7f2f/src/compiler/compile/render_dom/index.ts#L178

will add `$component_compiled_with_accessors`:`true` to each component instance which was compiled with `accessors = {true}`.
With  `$component_compiled_with_accessors` the accessors-check can't get any simpler, so it should be performance-safe:

`if (${leftObj}.$component_compiled_with_accessors) { ...`

inside the new "hack"-version:

```javascript

// performance --> 300 updates, throttling: off
// using $set(): 5.00 sec (60 fps) --> updates only corresponding component, scheduled flush

//const use_hack = false // 17.34 sec ( 17 fps )
const use_hack = true // 9.58 sec ( 31 fps ) --> updates only the corresponding component, but still flushes it after each change of each prop (not scheduled as with 'set()')


if(use_hack) {

  let leftObj = undefined
  let leftPropName = undefined

  if(node.left?.property?.name) leftPropName = node.left.property.name
  if((node.left?.object?.type === 'Identifier')) leftObj = node.left.object.name
  if((node.left?.object?.type === 'MemberExpression')) leftObj = node.left.object
						
  // if the node.left is 'Identifier'.'Identifier' or 'MemberExpression'.'Identifier'
  if(leftObj && leftPropName) {

    invalidate = b `if (${leftObj}.$component_compiled_with_accessors) {
        ${extra_args.length ? [node, ...extra_args] : node}
      } else {
        $$invalidate(${renderer.context_lookup.get(head.name).index}, ${node}, ${extra_args})
      }`[0]
    }

  else {
    invalidate = x `$$invalidate(${renderer.context_lookup.get(head.name).index}, ${node}, ${extra_args})`;
  }
}
else {
  invalidate = x `$$invalidate(${renderer.context_lookup.get(head.name).index}, ${node}, ${extra_args})`;
}

```

***pro / con "hack":***

*PRO*: **nearly doubles the performance / speed** when using accessors (updates only the corresponding component)
*CON*: **still flushes after each change of each prop** (not scheduled) so it just **cannot be as performant as using `$set()`**
*CON*: **bundle size could potentially become much larger** (code sections have two different versions wrapped in conditional statements). *Though I think this could be "fixed" by creating a new function extra for this purpose.*


***Conclusion so far***:

So (imo), the **most performant solution** would be replacing any accessor-statements with corresponding `$set()`-statements, means also omitting the standard setter-`flush()` (*otherwise we end up with the current accessors / setter implementation which is flushing after executing `$set()`*).


‚ùì  ***Conclusion leaves me with the question:***

In which scenario would an immediate `flush()` after prop change be **really important** and would have a (significant) advantage over using `$set()` (waiting for other props' update before the `flush()`)? ü§î

Feedback much appreciated! üëç

