#### Scenario:
right now, I have full-page loading app and adding svelte component was a breeze:

```js
import TestComponent from './admin/svelte/test.svelte';

new TestComponent({
    target: document.querySelector('.app-test'),
});
```

I couldn't be happier! But when ``<div class="app-test"></div>`` is created dynamically and injected into page; nothing happens.

It is pretty much what I expected anyways. 

I use [selector-observer ](https://github.com/josh/selector-observer) that triggers whenever some selector is added/removed from page. So my JS became:

```js
import {observe} from 'selector-observer'
import TestComponent from './admin/svelte/test.svelte';

observe('.app-test', {
    add(el) {
        new TestComponent({
            target: el,
        });
    }
});
```

and again; *perfection*, all worked! This would allow me to keep full-page loading (has some advantages in my scenario) and yet, I can add components dynamically. This worked with multiple ``div`` elements, each was new instance.


Because it worked so easy, I have to ask;

#### is what I am doing wrong/stupid/dangerous?

---

Sorry to ask but I did try to find answer but none of them was as simple as above.

nodes.body:
If anyone stumbles upon this, here is the final code for real component:

```html
<svelte-watch-live
    data-obstructions-url="http://example.com/url1"    <!-- URL is dynamically generated by backend -->
    data-feed-url="http://example.com/url2">           <!-- URL is dynamically generated by backend -->
</svelte-watch-live>
```


```js
import {observe} from 'selector-observer'

let wk = new WeakMap();

observe('svelte-watch-live', {
    add(el) {
        import('./watch_live_event.svelte').then(({default: WatchLive}) => {
            let component = new WatchLive({
                target: el,
                props: {
                    feedUrl: el.getAttribute('data-feed-url'),
                    obstructionsUrl: el.getAttribute('data-obstructions-url'),
                },
            });
            wk.set(el, component);
        })
    },
    remove(el) {
        let component = wk.get(el);
        component.$destroy();
        wk.delete(el);
    }
});
```

---

What happens here is that ``selector-observer`` will detect ``<svelte-watch-live>`` in HTML, create component, inject some props to it and connect element and component via WeakMap.

When element gets removed (some JS, or libs like barba, swup, turbolinks...), component is found from weakmap and manually destroyed. Tested it, works w/o problems.

