I have a workaround solves two problems and allows me to handle events.

https://github.com/bradphelan/svelte-x3dom-demo/blob/main/src/App.svelte
![2020-10-22_20-16-27](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/17650/96913171-93649780-14a3-11eb-8e6f-60a2f94b89d0.gif )


I needed to create a custom action like below to replace ``on:click``

https://github.com/bradphelan/svelte-x3dom-demo/blob/main/src/x3dom.ts
```

let r = ()=>{};

window.x3dom.runtime.ready = ()=>{
   r();
}

let loaded = new Promise((resolve) => {
    r = resolve;
});


export let onclick = (node, handler) => {
    // Don't register the event handler unless the x3dom is ready
    loaded.then(v=>{
        node.addEventListener("click", handler);           
    });

    return {
        destroy() {
            try {
                node.removeEventListener("click", handler);
            } catch (error) {
                console.warn("Cannot remove event handler from x3dom node");
                
            }
        },
    };
};
```

So two problem are handled above. 

1.)  Events can't be handled until x3dom is actually ready for them
2.)  By the time destroy is called it is too late to do it. The object is in a bad state.

With regards to (2). If, when registering the handler I immediately call ``removeEventListener`` afterward then no error occurs which suggests the problem is a matter of timing or perhaps x3dom has already cleaned up the object and disposed of internal state.

```
 node.addEventListener("click", handler);           
 node.removeEventListener("click", handler);
````

I have a repository where all this can be played with including the workaround https://github.com/bradphelan/svelte-x3dom-demo

