At the moment, there is only one way to declare reactive expressions - `$:`

I've seen many times that developers (mostly from other frameworks) aren't used to this syntax or they don't like it, for example because this syntax isn't used anywhere (including vanilla) except Svelte.

I propose a more manual, longhand version of reactive expression declaration in a more familiar style for JS developers.

(I couldn't find a normal name, so in these examples I'll just call it `manualReactivity`, but name can be easily changed).

Example of use of this feature:

```svelte
<script>
  import { manualReactivity } from 'svelte';

  let reactiveVariable = "I'm reactive";
  let secondReactiveVariable = "I'm too";
  
  function myFunction() {
    console.log('Svelte is universal');
  }


  // Current approach
  $: if(reactiveVariable) myFunction(); // or reactiveVariable && myFunction();


  // Manual approach
  manualReactivity([
    [reactiveVariable, myFunction()]
  ]);

  // OR(if only one array is given)
  manualReactivity([reactiveVariable, myFunction()]);


  // Variants of use:
  manualReactivity([
    [reactiveVariable, myFunction()], // pass array with dependency and expression
    [
      [reactiveVariable, secondReactiveVariable], // if there are several dependencies, the first parameter can be an array
      myFunction()
    ],
    () => {
      if(reactiveVariable) myFunction()  // If only a function is given, compiler automatically selects dependencies as in –°urrent approach
    }
  ]);
```


```javascript
  // Errors:
  manualReactivity([
    [reactiveVariable], // Error. Function is required.
    [
      reactiveVariable,
      myFunction(),
      secondReactiveVariable // Error. manualReactivity accepts only 2 parameters: dependencies and function
    ]
  ]);
```

This method also allows to extend Svelte reactivity capabilities by allowing choosing dependencies and collecting all reactive expressions in one place in a Svelte file.


And, which I personally really like, it allows to avoid multiple use of `$:`, which can improve appearance of the code


```svelte
<script>
  $: expressionOne(myProp);
  $: anotherOne(myProp);
  // many  "$:" later
  $: lastOne(anotherProp);

  // IMHO - looks better
  manualReactivity([
    [myProp, expressionOne()], // Or expressionOne(myProp)
    [myProp, anotherOne()],
    //...
    [lastOne, anotherProp()]
  ]);
</script>
```


## Drawbacks

- Basically, since a person spends less time on understanding the choice of dependencies for reactivity - the probability of using completely variables increases.

## Unresolved questions

* An idea is that it is possible to use the reactivity logic from the current approach, but it may take time for additional adaptation.
* Should variable with `manualReactivity` with parent dependencies be allowed to pass to child components?

