All animations/transitions in svelte are done through pure css, simply add the following to your global style sheet
```css
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  * {
    animation-delay: 0ms !important;
    animation-duration: 1ms !important;
  }
}
```

`svelte/motion` is an extension of `svelte/store`, if you know for sure that setting your values instantly won't break your uses of `spring` and `tweened`, the apis are so similar you'll most likely be fine just re-exporting them as `writable`s

```ts
import { spring as svelte_spring, tweened as svelte_tweened } from "svelte/motion";
import { writable } from "svelte/store";

const reduce_motion = matchMedia("(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)").matches;

export const spring = reduce_motion ? writable : svelte_spring;
export const tweened = reduce_motion ? writable : svelte_tweened;
```

That's honestly as far as you'll get in terms of support for that feature given the constrains set by the v3 design

This issue needs some debates.

Example)
```HTML
<script>
import { fade } from 'svelte/transition';
let arr = [1, 2, 3];
setTimeout(() => {
   arr = [1, 2];
}, 1000);
</script>

{#each arr as item, i (item)}
   <div transition:fade>
      <Item item={arr[i]}/>
   </div>
{/each}
```
Problem: `arr[2]` is `undefined` on changed but `Item` should expect `3`

