**Describe the bug**
If a reactive declaration is an assignment, Svelte automatically replaces `$:` with `let` in SSR mode if the variable on the left hand side hasn't been declared. It does this even if the left hand side is a member expression:

```svelte
<script>
  $: user = {};
  $: user.name = 'world';
</script>

<h1>Hello {user.name}!</h1>
```

```js
const App = create_ssr_component(($$result, $$props, $$bindings, $$slots) => {
  let user = {};
  let user.name = "world";
  return `<h1>Hello ${escape(user.name)}!</h1>`;
});
```

**To Reproduce**
https://svelte.dev/repl/b8f185ca9b104f4c8d08f2e5846cfaf0?version=3.24.1

**Expected behavior**
Only the `$: user = ...` declaration should have a `let` prepended.

**Severity**
Can be worked around (e.g. `$: true && (user.name = 'world');`) but it's a bit annoying. Relatively infrequent occurrence though.

**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
In normal TS, you can write stuff like:
```ts
function foo(value: number | string) {
  if (typeof value == 'number') {
    // Type checks successfully because this block would be unreachable if the value was a string.
    let foo: number = value;
  }
}
```
It's called refinements because it refines the type to a more precise one as you observe it.

In `{#if}` blocks, this does not appear to be supported. Say I have this type:
```ts
type Thing = {
  type: "success";
  value: number;
} | {
  type: "failure";
  error: string;
};
```
I try to use `{#if}` to render differently depending on the value:
```html
{#if thing.type == "success"}
  <p>Success! {thing.value}</p>
{/if}
```
Instead of working like it would for a normal if statement, it gives this error instead:
```
Property 'value' does not exist on type 'Thing'.
  Property 'value' does not exist on type '{ type: "success"; value: number; } | { type: "failure"; error: string; }'.ts(2
```

**Describe the solution you'd like**
I'd like if `{#if}` could somehow replicate the behavior of TS if statements.

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
I guess I can work around it somehow. Not sure how though, other than to disable typescript for most of my components or ignore all the errors. `npm run dev` still lets the code run despite the errors.

**How important is this feature to you?**
My code is full of errors and I don't know if what I'm writing is full of bugs.

**Additional context**
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1254344/89134701-f285c200-d4db-11ea-8922-06233cd2bb49.png)

