Oh, I think I figured it out. It's when you nest {#if} like in my screenshot.

I flattened out my {#if} and that fixed it. It looks like I can pretty consistently reproduce what's happening now, although it's not the same as what I described.

Errors:
```svelte
<script lang="typescript">
  interface Success {
    type: "success";
    value: number | null;
  }

  interface Failure {
    type: "failure";
  }

  type Thing = Success | Failure;

  export let thing: Thing;
</script>

{#if thing.type == 'success'}
  {#if thing.value != null} // Property 'value' does not exist on type 'Thing'. Property 'value' does not exist on type 'Failure'.
    <p>Success! {thing.value}</p> // Property 'value' does not exist on type 'Thing'. Property 'value' does not exist on type 'Failure'.
  {:else}
    <p>Success!</p>
  {/if}
{/if}
```

Works:
```svelte
{#if thing.type == 'success' && thing.value != null}
  <p>Success! {thing.value}</p>
{:else if thing.type == 'success'}
  <p>Success!</p>
{/if}
```

Until now I don't know the exact reason. But if you still want to do that, Try using `setTimeout` & `bind:value` instead `value`: (*this works*)

**Example:**
```js
<script>	
  let value = "0";

  function set() {		
     setTimeout(()=>{
        value = "";
     })
  }
